message: Rep. Tom Price worked as a doctor for nearly 20 years before serving the people of Georgia's 6th District in the U.S. House of Representatives. Now, he has been nominated to serve as the next Secretary of Health and Human Services. He is an excellent choice. I have no doubt he will work tirelessly to ensure all Americans have quality, affordable healthcare. Learn more about him here:

Today is the first day of the 115th Congress. I'm honored to represent #CA45 and excited to implement House Republicans' #BetterWay agenda.

I am humbled to serve the people of #CA45 in the U.S. House of Representatives. It is a tremendous honor to represent the people of Orange County, and it is a responsibility I take very seriously.  As we begin the 115th Congress, we have a renewed opportunity to fulfill our duty to the American people by enacting legislation that will put our country back on the right path. As part of a unified Republican government, I am excited to implement our #BetterWay agenda to grow our economy, keep us safe, improve access to healthcare, and increase opportunities for all Americans.  I look forward to working with my colleagues on both sides of the aisle to implement solutions. Please do not hesitate to contact our office if we can be of service to you in any way.

I voted for the Midnight Rules Relief Act because last minute regulations from the Obama Administration don't serve the American people. Outgoing Administrations shouldn't rush to implement regulations that end up costing American taxpayers billions of dollars. The House has passed legislation to prevent it, and it is my hope the Senate considers this bill expeditiously.

I'm honored by the opportunity to serve on the House Committee on Energy and Commerce this Congress. With a unified Republican government, we will put our country back on the right path. The Committee will play a critical role in reforming our healthcare system, keeping energy affordable, and growing our economy. I'm excited to work on these pressing issues and enact real solutions for the American people.   Many of my constituents work in industries that are directly affected by the Committee‚Äôs work, and serving in this new role will allow me to continue to serve as an effective advocate for them.  I'm looking forward to working with the Committee on issues that impact the people I represent.

When I took the oath of office, I swore to protect & defend the U.S. Constitution. Today, I joined my colleagues in reading our founding document on the House Floor. We are committed to upholding the Constitution and the enduring principles for which it stands.

Across the country, our families and businesses are being crushed by the weight of government overregulation. Regulations are necessary, but when they overreach, they do far more harm than good. House Republicans know that complex and burdensome overregulation is killing jobs and stifling our economy. Regulating sensibly is a crucial piece of our #BetterWay agenda, & it's exactly why we passed the REINS Act today.  This bill would give Congress a simple up or down vote on major federal regulations that impose significant costs and burdens on families and businesses.  The American people deserve accountability and transparency in the regulatory process.  Unlike federal agency bureaucrats, Congress is accountable to the American people.  Our government is one of checks and balances, and the REINS Act will provide a necessary check on the executive branch‚Äôs reckless regulatory actions. I'm proud to have cosponsored this legislation & pleased to see it pass the House with bipartisan support.

After more than 27 hours of extensive, public debate, the House Committee on Energy and Commerce passed the American Health Care Act #AHCA. Last night, I spoke about the hardships my constituents have experienced under the Affordable Care Act. Many have told me they are faced with significantly higher premiums, increased co-pays, and loss of their healthcare plans. Sadly, many simply cannot afford health insurance because of the ACA. The message I‚Äôve received is clear: the ACA is not working for the people I represent. Our constituents need healthcare plans and programs that work for them, not Washington. It's our duty to rescue this failing healthcare system and develop a system that offers Americans access to quality, patient-centered care. Passage of the #AHCA is a critical step towards that goal.

Fact Check:  Online consumer privacy protections remain unchanged, contrary to the recent flood of misinformation.  Last week‚Äôs broadband privacy vote did not remove or change any existing Internet consumer privacy protections or standards because the Federal Communications Commission‚Äôs rules were never put in place.  The Federal Trade Commission has been the chief enforcement agency of privacy protection and data security for decades.  By continuing to empower the FTC to police broadband privacy, Internet users will remain protected under existing privacy standards.  Our nation‚Äôs chief privacy enforcer and the chief communications regulator set the record straight on the broadband privacy vote in this Washington Post Op-Ed.

Bringing attention and awareness to this issue is a critical first step to stop these heinous crimes.  Sadly, men and women serving in our armed forces experience unacceptably high rates of sexual assault. These service members also face cyber-harassment and the distribution of intimate photos and videos on social media, as evidenced by the recent ‚ÄúMarine United‚Äù scandal.  To deter such unacceptable behavior that damages our military‚Äôs morale, I cosponsored the PRIVATE Act. Offered by Air Force veteran and Arizona Representative Martha McSally, this legislation would criminalize this disgraceful behavior under the Uniform Code of Military Justice. This important reform would give military prosecutors the necessary tools to take legal action against those who carry out this reprehensible behavior.  I am pleased my colleagues in Congress are making sexual assault awareness and prevention a top priority and look forward to working with them to put an end to this appalling epidemic.

Our veterans are the backbone of our nation and heroes among us.  They deserve the highest quality health care possible through the VA, no questions asked.  Three years ago this week we learned that a wait time manipulation scandal resulted in dozens of veterans dying while awaiting treatment at a Phoenix VA hospital.  Unfortunately, pervasive problems continue to plague the VA system, threatening the lives of millions of veterans who rely on the VA for medical care.  Just this week, an alarming report revealed that conditions within the Washington, DC VA Medical Center are so dire that hospital patients are actually in danger.  This conduct is inexcusable, and I will continue to push for meaningful reforms to the VA.  The House of Representatives has taken important steps to address the VA‚Äôs systemic problems and ensure our veterans receive timely and quality care.   We recently sent a bipartisan bill to the President‚Äôs desk to improve the VA Choice Program, which will reduce out-of-pocket costs for veterans and remove current barriers to the timely disclosure of veteran medical records.  The House also passed legislation last month to address the glaring lack of accountability within the VA. The VA Accountability First Act would provide the VA Secretary increased flexibility to remove poorly performing employees and protect whistle-blowers who expose misconduct.  Providing our veterans with quality, reliable health coverage is a top priority, and I will continue advocating for VA reforms that prioritize the well-being of our nation‚Äôs veterans.

Over the last decade, opioid addiction has skyrocketed across the nation.  In my district located in Orange County, California, opioid-related drug overdoses and deaths have tragically kept pace with the rapid increase in abuse.  Last week, I signed a bipartisan letter to the Secretary of Health and Human Services regarding the implementation of the Comprehensive Addiction Recovery Act (CARA), which provides resources and necessary reforms to address the nation‚Äôs opioid epidemic.  CARA seeks to ensure that patients are offered, and physicians are trained on, a full range of FDA-approved treatment options. Prior to this legislation, pain medication treatments were often prescribed based on the patient‚Äôs setting of care, not the patient‚Äôs needs.  We can no longer accept such casual prescription of these powerful and addictive drugs that often lead to the abuse of illegal substances like heroin.  I applaud my fellow Members of Congress who remain engaged in our efforts to combat opioid abuse.  I am committed to ensuring CARA is fully implemented to put an end to this epidemic, which claims far too many lives.

The opioid epidemic continues to ravage our Nation. A new report from JAMA Pediatrics found that only 25% of young Americans suffering from opioid use disorder (OUD), are receiving the treatment medications they need to overcome OUD.  Sadly, treatment rates among women and minorities are even lower.     These startling statistics underscore the need for timely implementation of the Comprehensive Addiction and Recovery Act (CARA), which was signed into law last year. As part of the House Republicans' 21st Century Cures Act, CARA increased funds to help states with opioid addiction and prevention efforts, including the purchase of additional life-saving drugs to reverse opioid overdoses.  By focusing on treatment and intervention programs, in conjunction with increased monitoring of prescription opioid-based pain killers, we can help put an end to this epidemic.

Common sense solutions can help hard working Californians prevent property damage caused by floods, which is why I am a proud cosponsor of the Repeatedly Flooded Communities Preparation Act.  This important bill would require communities with known flooding issues to take necessary steps to better protect themselves from reoccurring damages.  Each year, between 1,000 and 10,000 floods occur on California properties that have flooded in the past, and claims on these properties account for 25-30% of the National Flood Insurance Program‚Äôs (NFIP) losses. This bill would ensure NFIP funds are better utilized at the local level to help communities better address their unique needs while promoting the effective and efficient use of taxpayer dollars.

The bipartisan Nuclear Waste Policy Amendments Act of 2017, approved at today‚Äôs House Committee on Energy and Commerce markup, will develop a path forward for the interim and permanent storage of spent nuclear fuel located throughout the country.  I appreciate the kind words of Chairman Greg Walden, recognizing our work on this issue, and thank Congressman John Shimkus for his hard work to address these concerns in the legislation.
